    683          /***************************************************************************//**
    684           * @brief
    685           *   Register a callback in the TEMP driver
    686           *
    687           * @details
    688           *   This function is used for registering an application callback when the
    689           *   temperature changes. Note that when calling this function an application
    690           *   must specify the direction of the temperature change, use
    691           *   @ref TEMPDRV_LIMIT_LOW to receive a callback when the temperature drops
    692           *   below the specified temp and use @ref TEMPDRV_LIMIT_HIGH to receive a
    693           *   callback when the temperature increases above the specified temp.
    694           *
    695           * @note
    696           *   The user registered callback will be cleared once it's called. This means
    697           *   that the callback functions are not persistent, and have to be managed by
    698           *   the application. This feature can be used to implement a user controlled
    699           *   hysteresis. So for instance to register a callback at 50&deg;C with a
    700           *   5&deg;C hysteresis you can first register a callback at 50&deg;C or above
    701           *   using this function, and when the callback fires you can use this function
    702           *   again to register a callback when the temperature decreases to 45&deg;C or
    703           *   below. Each time a callback fires you only need to call the
    704           *   @ref TEMPDRV_RegisterCallback() function, there is no need to call
    705           *   @ref TEMPDRV_UnregisterCallback().
    706           *
    707           * @details
    708           *   It's important to know the current temperature before calling this
    709           *   function. Attempting to register a callback that would fire immediately
    710           *   is not supported and will result in a return value of
    711           *   @ref ECODE_EMDRV_TEMPDRV_BAD_LIMIT. Examples of an illegal scenario would
    712           *   be to register a callback for a temperature that is higher than the current
    713           *   temperature and with a limit set to @ref TEMPDRV_LIMIT_LOW.
    714           *
    715           * @param[in] temp
    716           *   Temperature to trigger on given in number of &deg;C.
    717           *
    718           * @param[in] limit
    719           *   Limit type, refer to @ref TEMPDRV_LimitType_t. Using @ref TEMPDRV_LIMIT_LOW
    720           *   will register a callback when the EMU temperature reaches \p temp &deg;C
    721           *   or lower, and using @ref TEMPDRV_LIMIT_HIGH will register a callback when
    722           *   the EMU temperature reaches \p temp &deg;C or higher.
    723           *
    724           * @param[in] callback
    725           *   User defined function to call when temperature threshold is reached or passed.
    726           *
    727           * @return
